@startuml
!include ../style.puml

title Hybrid Timestamps Flow Through The Workshop

' [step1 {"name":"Begin transaction goes to coordinator"}]
actor "Client" as client
participant "Txn Coordinator\nhash(txnId)" as coord
participant "Key Replica\nhash(key)" as replica

client -> coord: BeginTransaction(txnId, clientTime=(1000,0))
activate coord
coord -> coord: merge local clock with clientTime
coord --> client: readTimestamp=(1000,1)
deactivate coord
' [/step1]

' [step2 {"name":"Write carries both snapshot and propagated HLC"}]
client -> replica: TxnWrite(key, value,\nreadTs=(1000,1), clientTime=(1000,2))
activate replica
replica -> replica: hybridClock.tick(clientTime)
replica -> replica: assign intent timestamp\nusing local HLC
replica --> client: TxnWriteResponse(propagatedTime=(1005,0))
deactivate replica
' [/step2]

' [step3 {"name":"Client merges returned time"}]
client -> client: hybridClock.tick((1005,0))

note right of client
Every request/response carries time.
The client keeps learning a later HLC
from replicas and reuses it on future RPCs.
end note
' [/step3]

' [step4 {"name":"Commit returns final commit timestamp"}]
client -> coord: Commit(txnId, participantWrites,\nclientTime=(1005,1))
activate coord
coord -> coord: choose commit timestamp\nfrom merged HLC state
coord --> client: CommitResponse(commitTs=(1010,0))
deactivate coord

note over client, replica
This is why the workshop can stay decentralized:
no global timestamp oracle is needed.
Ordering emerges from HLC propagation plus routing.
end note
' [/step4]

@enduml
